e]] featuring [[Bun B]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2005 in music]]\n*[[List of Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles of 2005]]\n*[[List of Billboard Hot 100 top-ten singles in 2005]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Top Hot 100 Hits}}\n\n[[Category:2005 record charts|United States Hot 100 Year-end]]\n[[Category:Billboard charts]]\n", "name_user": "36.74.185.224", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eList)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billboard_Year-End_Hot_100_singles_of_2005"}
{"title_page": "Bernardita Catalla", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Philippine name|Leonido|Catalla}}{{short description|Philippine ambassador}}\n{{short description|Philippine ambassador}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Bernardita Catalla\n| image              = Ambassador Bernardita Catalla (cropped).jpg\n| alt                =\n| caption            = Ambassador Catalla in February 2018\n| birth_name         =\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1958|02|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Makati]], Philippines\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|04|02|1958|02|18}}\n| death_place        = [[Beirut]], Lebanon\n| nationality        = Filipina\n| education          = [[University of the Philippines Los Ba\u00f1os]]<br>[[University of the Philippines Diliman]]<br>[[International Institute of Social Studies]]\n| occupation         = Career diplomat\n| years_active       = 1993\u20132020\n}}\n\n'''Bernardita Leonido Catalla''' (February 18, 1958 \u2013 April 2, 2020) was a Filippina career diplomat who was last appointed as the Philippine ambassador to [[Lebanon]]. Prior to her posting in Lebanon, she was also assigned to [[Hong Kong]], [[Indonesia]], and [[Malaysia]].<ref name=scmp>{{cite news |last1=Carvalho |first1=Raquel |title=Bernardita Catalla, the Philippines\u2019 former consul general to Hong Kong, dies of coronavirus in Beirut |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/diplomacy/article/3078175/bernardita-catalla-philippines-former-consul-general-hong-kong |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Philippine ambassador to Lebanon dies of coronavirus |url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/philippine-ambassador-to-lebanon-dies-of-coronavirus-1.1000572 |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=The National.ae |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nCatalla was born on February 18, 1958 in [[Makati]], then a part of the [[Rizal|Province of Rizal]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ulep |first1=Bombo Jerald |title=PH Ambassador to Lebanon Bernardita Catalla, pumanaw dahil sa COVID-19 |url=https://www.bomboradyo.com/phl-ambassador-to-lebanon-bernardita-catalla-pumanaw-dahil-sa-covid-19/ |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=Bombo Radyo Philippines |date=April 2, 2020 |language=Filipino}}</ref> She graduated in 1979 from [[University of the Philippines Los Ba\u00f1os]] with a Bachelor of Arts degree in communication arts.<ref>{{cite web |title=Speakers: Bernardita Leonido Catalla |url=https://amchamhk.eventbank.com/event/2099/speakers.html |publisher=[[United States Chamber of Commerce]] |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> From 1987 to 1993, she studied at the [[University of the Philippines Diliman]] for her master's degree in communication research and in 1991, she graduated with a Master of Arts degree in development studies from the [[International Institute of Social Studies]] at [[Erasmus University Rotterdam]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/groups/259622497497812/permalink/1769966839796696/|title=International Institute of Social Studies (ISS)|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://beirutpe.dfa.gov.ph/images/2018/amb-cv/Amb-Bernardita-Catalla.pdf|title=Amb. Bernardita Catalla Curriculum Vitae|last=|first=|date=2018|website=Philippine Embassy in Beirut, Lebanon|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Philippine Ambassador to Lebanon Presents Credentials to the President of Lebanon 01.jpg|thumb|left|Ambassador Catalla presenting her credentials to President [[Michel Aoun]] of Lebanon on January 10, 2018]]\n\nCatalla first entered the Philippine Foreign Service in 1993.<ref name=ASEAN>{{cite web |title=Bernardita Leonido Catalla: Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary |url=https://beirutpe.dfa.gov.ph/images/2018/amb-cv/Amb-Bernardita-Catalla.pdf |publisher=Department of Foreign Affairs Philippines |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> She was the principal assistant and then acting director of the [[ASEAN]] office from 1994 to 1995.<ref name=ASEAN/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Viray |first1=Patricia Lourdes |title='Her smile, laughter will be a guiding light': Philippine envoy in Lebanon succumbs to COVID-19 |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/04/02/2005011/her-smile-laughter-will-be-guiding-light-philippine-envoy-lebanon-succumbs-covid-19 |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=PhilStar |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1996 to 2001, she was assigned at the Embassy of the Philippines in [[Kuala Lumpur|Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia]] as Vice Consul and then Consul.<ref name=\"scmp\" />\n\nShe was recalled back to the Home Office to become the Director of the Office of United Nations and International Organizations from 2001 to 2002 and Passport Director from 2002 to 2005.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://dfa.gov.ph/dfa-news/statements-and-advisoriesupdate/26554-statement-on-the-demise-of-honorable-bernardita-m-catalla-philippine-ambassador-to-lebanon|title=Statement: On the Demise of Honorable Bernardita L. Catalla, Philippine Ambassador to Lebanon|last=|first=|date=April 2, 2020|website=Department of Foreign Affairs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe was consul of the Philippine Embassy in [[Jakarta]] from 2005 to 2011 and Director of the Office of Asia & Pacific Affairs at the Home Office from 2011 to 2014.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nShe was posted to the Philippine Consulate in [[Hong Kong]] as Consul-General from 2014 to 2017.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/sunwebhk/photos/a.210926958972150/683594245038750/?type=3|title=The SUN Hong Kong|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> During her stint in Hong Kong, she spearheaded the amendment of contracts of foreign domestic helpers to include a ban on dangerous window cleaning, which according to The Sun Hong Kong, was her biggest legacy to the Filipino community in the region.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.sunwebhk.com/2020/04/ambassador-and-ex-hk-congen-bernie.html?m=1|title=Ambassador and ex-HK Congen Bernie Catalla succumbs to COVID-19|date=April 2, 2020|work=The Sun Hong Kong|access-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter that, she was promoted to the Embassy in Beirut, Lebanon as Ambassador from 2017 up to her death in 2020.<ref name=\":0\" /> As Ambassador to Lebanon, she spearheaded the voluntary mass repatriation program of [[Overseas Filipinos|OFWs]] in the country.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Death ==\nIn April 2020, she died of [[COVID-19]] in Beirut, Lebanon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/256741-philippine-ambassador-lebanon-bernardita-catalla-dies-coronavirus|title=PH ambassador to Lebanon dies of coronavirus|last=Tomacruz|first=Sofia|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/pinoyabroad/news/732330/philippine-envoy-to-lebanon-dies-of-covid-19/story/|title=Philippine envoy to Lebanon dies of COVID-19 complications|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/overseas/04/02/20/ph-envoy-to-lebanon-dies-of-covid-19-complications|title=PH envoy to Lebanon dies of COVID-19 complications|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnation.inquirer.net/186474/fwd-dfa-on-death-of-ph-top-diplomat-to-lebanon|title=PH Ambassador to Lebanon succumbs to COVID-19|last=Ramos|first=Christia Marie|website=globalnation.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Rocamora|first=Joyce Ann|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1098584|title=PH envoy to Lebanon dies of Covid-19: DFA|date=April 2, 2020|work=Philippine News Agency|access-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Catalla, Bernardita}}\n\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the Philippines to Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:People from Makati]]\n[[Category:University of the Philippines Los Ba\u00f1os alumni]]\n[[Category:International Institute of Social Studies alumni]]\n[[Category:Filipino women diplomats]]\n[[Category:University of the Philippines Diliman alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Philippine name|Leonido|Catalla}}{{short description|Philippine ambassador}}\n{{short description|Philippine ambassador}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Bernardita Catalla\n| image              = Ambassador Bernardita Catalla (cropped).jpg\n| alt                =\n| caption            = Ambassador Catalla in February 2018\n| birth_name         =\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1958|02|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Makati]], Philippines\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2020|04|02|1958|02|18}}\n| death_place        = [[Beirut]], Lebanon\n| nationality        = Filipina\n| education          = [[University of the Philippines Los Ba\u00f1os]]<br>[[University of the Philippines Diliman]]<br>[[International Institute of Social Studies]]\n| occupation         = Career diplomat\n| years_active       = 1993\u20132020\n}}\n\n'''Bernardita Leonido Catalla''' (February 18, 1958 \u2013 April 2, 2020) was a Filippina career diplomat who was last appointed as the Philippine ambassador to [[Lebanon]]. Prior to her posting in Lebanon, she was also assigned to [[Hong Kong]], [[Indonesia]], and [[Malaysia]].<ref name=scmp>{{cite news |last1=Carvalho |first1=Raquel |title=Bernardita Catalla, the Philippines\u2019 former consul general to Hong Kong, dies of coronavirus in Beirut |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/diplomacy/article/3078175/bernardita-catalla-philippines-former-consul-general-hong-kong |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=[[South China Morning Post]] |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Philippine ambassador to Lebanon dies of coronavirus |url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/mena/philippine-ambassador-to-lebanon-dies-of-coronavirus-1.1000572 |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=The National.ae |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nCatalla was born on February 18, 1958 in [[Makati]], then a part of the [[Rizal|Province of Rizal]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ulep |first1=Bombo Jerald |title=PH Ambassador to Lebanon Bernardita Catalla, pumanaw dahil sa COVID-19 |url=https://www.bomboradyo.com/phl-ambassador-to-lebanon-bernardita-catalla-pumanaw-dahil-sa-covid-19/ |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=Bombo Radyo Philippines |date=April 2, 2020 |language=Filipino}}</ref> She graduated in 1979 from [[University of the Philippines Los Ba\u00f1os]] with a Bachelor of Arts degree in communication arts.<ref>{{cite web |title=Speakers: Bernardita Leonido Catalla |url=https://amchamhk.eventbank.com/event/2099/speakers.html |publisher=[[United States Chamber of Commerce]] |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> From 1987 to 1993, she studied at the [[University of the Philippines Diliman]] for her masters degree in communication research and in 1991, she graduated with a Master of Arts degree in development studies from the [[International Institute of Social Studies]] at [[Erasmus University Rotterdam]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/groups/259622497497812/permalink/1769966839796696/|title=International Institute of Social Studies (ISS)|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://beirutpe.dfa.gov.ph/images/2018/amb-cv/Amb-Bernardita-Catalla.pdf|title=Amb. Bernardita Catalla Curriculum Vitae|last=|first=|date=2018|website=Philippine Embassy in Beirut, Lebanon|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Philippine Ambassador to Lebanon Presents Credentials to the President of Lebanon 01.jpg|thumb|left|Ambassador Catalla presenting her credentials to President [[Michel Aoun]] of Lebanon on January 10, 2018]]\n\nCatalla first entered the Philippine Foreign Service in 1993.<ref name=ASEAN>{{cite web |title=Bernardita Leonido Catalla: Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary |url=https://beirutpe.dfa.gov.ph/images/2018/amb-cv/Amb-Bernardita-Catalla.pdf |publisher=Department of Foreign Affairs Philippines |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> She was the principal assistant and then acting director of the [[ASEAN]] office from 1994 to 1995.<ref name=ASEAN/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Viray |first1=Patricia Lourdes |title='Her smile, laughter will be a guiding light': Philippine envoy in Lebanon succumbs to COVID-19 |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/04/02/2005011/her-smile-laughter-will-be-guiding-light-philippine-envoy-lebanon-succumbs-covid-19 |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=PhilStar |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1996 to 2001, she was assigned at the Embassy of the Philippines in [[Kuala Lumpur|Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia]] as Vice Consul and then Consul.<ref name=\"scmp\" />\n\nShe was recalled back to the Home Office to become the Director of the Office of United Nations and International Organizations from 2001 to 2002 and Passport Director from 2002 to 2005.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://dfa.gov.ph/dfa-news/statements-and-advisoriesupdate/26554-statement-on-the-demise-of-honorable-bernardita-m-catalla-philippine-ambassador-to-lebanon|title=Statement: On the Demise of Honorable Bernardita L. Catalla, Philippine Ambassador to Lebanon|last=|first=|date=April 2, 2020|website=Department of Foreign Affairs|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe was consul of the Philippine Embassy in [[Jakarta]] from 2005 to 2011 and Director of the Office of Asia & Pacific Affairs at the Home Office from 2011 to 2014.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nShe was posted to the Philippine Consulate in [[Hong Kong]] as Consul-General from 2014 to 2017.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/sunwebhk/photos/a.210926958972150/683594245038750/?type=3|title=The SUN Hong Kong|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> During her stint in Hong Kong, she spearheaded the amendment of contracts of foreign domestic helpers to include a ban on dangerous window cleaning, which according to The Sun Hong Kong, was her biggest legacy to the Filipino community in the region.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.sunwebhk.com/2020/04/ambassador-and-ex-hk-congen-bernie.html?m=1|title=Ambassador and ex-HK Congen Bernie Catalla succumbs to COVID-19|date=April 2, 2020|work=The Sun Hong Kong|access-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter that, she was promoted to the Embassy in Beirut, Lebanon as Ambassador from 2017 up to her death in 2020.<ref name=\":0\" /> As Ambassador to Lebanon, she spearheaded the voluntary mass repatriation program of [[Overseas Filipinos|OFWs]] in the country.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Death ==\nIn April 2020, she died of [[COVID-19]] in Beirut, Lebanon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/256741-philippine-ambassador-lebanon-bernardita-catalla-dies-coronavirus|title=PH ambassador to Lebanon dies of coronavirus|last=Tomacruz|first=Sofia|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/pinoyabroad/news/732330/philippine-envoy-to-lebanon-dies-of-covid-19/story/|title=Philippine envoy to Lebanon dies of COVID-19 complications|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/overseas/04/02/20/ph-envoy-to-lebanon-dies-of-covid-19-complications|title=PH envoy to Lebanon dies of COVID-19 complications|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnation.inquirer.net/186474/fwd-dfa-on-death-of-ph-top-diplomat-to-lebanon|title=PH Ambassador to Lebanon succumbs to COVID-19|last=Ramos|first=Christia Marie|website=globalnation.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Rocamora|first=Joyce Ann|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1098584|title=PH envoy to Lebanon dies of Covid-19: DFA|date=April 2, 2020|work=Philippine News Agency|access-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Catalla, Bernardita}}\n\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the Philippines to Lebanon]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Lebanon]]\n[[Category:People from Makati]]\n[[Category:University of the Philippines Los Ba\u00f1os alumni]]\n[[Category:International Institute of Social Studies alumni]]\n[[Category:Filipino women diplomats]]\n[[Category:University of the Philippines Diliman alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and education:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: masters degree \u2192 master's degree", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernardita_Catalla"}
{"title_page": "PostBank Uganda", "text_new": "{{Infobox company |\n  name   = PostBank Uganda|\n  logo   = |\n  type   = Private|\n  slogan = |\n  foundation     = 1926|\n  location       =  4 - 6 Nkrumah Road<br/>[[Kampala]], [[Uganda]] |\n  key_people     =  '''Obella Oode'''<br/>[[Chairman]] <br/> '''[[Julius Kakeeto]]'''<br/>[[Managing Director]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pmldaily.com/business/2019/11/postbank-uganda-announces-new-managing-director.html |date=11 November 2019 | publisher=PML Daily |author=Javia Ssebwami |access-date=3 April 2020 |\ntitle=Post Bank Uganda announces new managing director |place=Kampala}}</ref>|\n  num_employees  = |\n  assets         = US$54 million<br/>(UGX:135.7 billion) (2012)|\n  revenue        ={{profit}} US$1.7 million<br/>(UGX:4.28 billion) (2012)|\n  industry       = [[Financial Services]]|\n  products       = [[Loans]], [[cheque|Checking]], [[Savings]], [[Investments]]|\n  homepage       = [http://www.postbank.co.ug/ Homepage]\n}}\n\n'''PostBank Uganda''' is a non-bank credit institution in [[Uganda]]. Its activities are supervised by the [[Bank of Uganda]], the country's [[central bank]] and national banking regulator.<ref name=\"Regulator\">{{cite web|first=.|last=BOU|accessdate=21 June 2015\n|url=https://www.bou.or.ug/opencms/bou/bou-downloads/financial_institutions/2013/CREDIT-INSTITUTIONS-CIs-AS-AT-MARCH-31-2013.pdf|title=List of Licensed Credit Institutions In Uganda As At March 2013|publisher=[[Bank of Uganda]] (BOU)}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n{{asof|December 2012}}, PostBank Uganda was a small, but growing credit institution whose assets were estimated at US$54 million (UGX:135.7 billion).<ref>{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.sbreview.net/index.php/park-blog/225-mixed-fortunes-for-banks-in-2012|title=Mixed Fortunes for Banks In 2012|date=21 May 2013|first=Editors|last=By|accessdate=29 May 2014|publisher=Summit Business Review (Uganda)}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nPostBank Uganda has been in existence since 1926. It started out as a department in the Post Office. In February 1998 PostBank Uganda Limited was incorporated in accordance with the Communications Act of 1997 to take over the operations of the former Post Office Savings department.\n\nPostBank Uganda was incorporated under the Companies Act in February 1998 as a limited liability company. The bank's operations are supervised by the Bank of Uganda under the Financial Institutions Act. It is classified as a Tier II Institution (Non-Bank Credit Institution), by the Bank of Uganda.<ref name=\"Regulator\"/>\n\nPostBank Uganda  subscribes to the Depositors Insurance Scheme at Bank of Uganda. If PostBank Uganda fails, the bank's depositors are insured up to Sh 3 million (approximately US$1,600.00) in 2009, per eligible account. In 2009, PostBank Uganda applied to the Bank of Uganda to become a fully licensed [[commercial bank]].<ref>{{cite web|newspaper=[[New Vision]] (Kampala)|url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/13/676429|\ntitle=PostBank Launches Land Loan|date=30 March 2009|accessdate=29 May 2014|first=Josephine|last=Maseruka}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Ugandan media sources reported hat the government was planning to merge Postabank Uganda with [[Pride Microfinance Limited]], to form an agricultural bank.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=3 April 2016| url=http://newz.ug/2016/02/27/government-to-merge-post-bank-and-pride-microfinance-to-form-an-agricultural-bank/|date=27 February 2016 |\ntitle= Government to merge Post Bank and Pride Microfinance to form an agricultural Bank| publisher=Newz.ug (NZU) |last=NZU |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n==Ownership==\nPostBank Uganda is wholly owned by the [[Government of Uganda]].{{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n\n==Branch network==\nAs of May 2014, PostBank Uganda maintained a branch network of 32 fixed branches and 17 mobile banking units, totaling 49 branches.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=29 May 2014|\nurl=http://postbank.co.ug/index9c1f.html?option=com_content&view=article&id=22&Itemid=29|title=List of PostBank Branches|publisher=PostBank Uganda}}</ref>\n\n===Fixed branches===\n\n# Arua Branch - [[Arua]]\n# Bombo Branch - [[Bombo, Uganda|Bombo]]\n# Bugoloobi Branch - Bugoloobi, Kampala\n# City Branch - Nkrumah Road, Kampala (Head Office)\n# Entebbe Branch - [[Entebbe]]\n# Fort Portal Branch - [[Fort Portal]]\n# Gulu Branch - [[Gulu]]\n# Hoima Branch - [[Hoima]]\n# Iganga Branch - [[Iganga]]<ref>{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/21/675456|title=Central Bank commends PostBank|publisher=[[New Vision]]|date=21 March 2009|\naccessdate=29 May 2014|first=Donald|last=Kiirya}}</ref>\n# Jinja Branch - [[Jinja, Uganda|Jinja]]\n# Kabale Branch - [[Kabale]]\n# Kakiri Branch - [[Kakiri]]\n# Kampala Road Branch - Kampala Road, Kampala\n# Kamwenge Branch - [[Kamwenge]]<ref>{{cite web|\nurl=http://allafrica.com/stories/200910261083.html|title=Uganda: Post Bank Goes to Kamwenge|first=Hope|last=Mafaranga|date=25 October 2009|accessdate=29 May 2014|publisher=[[New Vision]] via [[AllAfrica.com]]}}</ref>\n# Kanungu Branch - [[Kanungu]]<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=29 May 2014|\nurl=http://allafrica.com/stories/201011070093.html|title=Uganda: Kanungu Gets Its Second Commercial Bank|first=Patson|last=Baraire| date=7 November 2010|publisher=[[New Vision]] via [[AllAfrica.com]]}}</ref>\n# Kasese Branch - [[Kasese]]\n# Kayunga Branch - [[Kayunga]]\n# Kitgum Branch - [[Kitgum]]\n# Lacor Branch - [[Lacor Hospital]], [[Gulu]]\n# Lira Branch - [[Lira, Uganda|Lira]]\n# Masaka Branch - [[Masaka]]\n# Mbale Branch - [[Mbale]]\n# Mbarara Branch - [[Mbarara]]\n# Mubende Branch - [[Mubende]]\n# Nakasongola Branch - [[Nakasongola]]\n# Ndeeba Branch - [[Ndeeba]], Kampala\n# Nkrumah Road Branch - Nkrumah Road, Kampala\n# Ntungamo Branch - [[Ntungamo]]\n# Soroti Branch - [[Soroti]]\n# Wandegeya Branch - [[Wandegeya]], Kampala\n# William Street Branch - William Street Kampala\n# Koome Island Branch - [[Koome Island]]<ref>{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Commodities/-/688610/1109788/-/ccacmv/-/index.html|title=Banks Intensify Branch Growth to Raise Customer Base|first=Faridah|last=Kulabako|date=18 February 2011|\npublisher=[[Daily Monitor]]|accessdate=29 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Mobile branches===\n\nThe mobile branches are located in the following towns and districts:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theceomagazine-ug.com/blog/2014/01/06/banking-on-wheelsbanks-innovatively-reaching-out-to-the-unbanked-in-remote-areas/|title=Banking On Wheels: Banks Innovatively Reaching Out to The Unbanked In Remote Areas|\ndate=6 January 2014|accessdate=5 June 2014|first=Taddewo|\nlast=Senyonyi|publisher=The CEO Magazine (Kampala)}}</ref>\n# [[Budaka town|Budaka]] - [[Budaka District]]\n# [[Bududa]] - [[Bududa District]]\n# [[Bukedea]] - [[Bukedea District]]\n# [[Butaleja]] - [[Butaleja District]]\n# [[Fort Portal]] - [[Kabarole District]]\n# [[Kamwenge]] - [[Kamwenge District]]\n# [[Kapchorwa]] - [[Kapchorwa District]]\n# [[Kibaale]] - [[Kibaale District]]\n# [[Kyegegwa]] - [[Kyegegwa District]]<ref>{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.theworkzine.com/business/the-entreprenuer/the-ugandan-millionaire|title=The Ugandan Millionaire|date=28 September 2010|\naccessdate=29 May 2014|publisher=Theworkzine.com|first=Ishita| last=Ghosh}}</ref>\n# [[Kyenjojo]] - [[Kyenjojo District]]\n# [[Manafwa]] - [[Manafwa District]]\n# [[Pallisa]] - [[Pallisa District]]\n# [[Sironko]] - [[Sironko District]]\n# [[Tororo]] - [[Tororo District]]\n\n==Governance==\nThe activities of PostBank Uganda are directed by its [[board of directors]]. {{asof|May 2014}}, the [[chairman]] of the board was Obella Oode. The [[managing director]] and [[chief executive officer]] was Stephen Mukweli. The current board was installed in 2012 for a five-year term. The day-to-day activities of the bank are supervised by a team of ten bank managers, headed by the managing director.<ref>{{cite web|first=Patrick|last=Jaramogi|date=4 April 2012|url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/mobile/Detail.aspx?NewsID=630105&CatID=3|accessdate=29 May 2014|publisher=[[New Vision]]|title=Post Bank Gets New Board}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Banks}}\n*[[Banking in Uganda]]\n*[[List of banks in Uganda]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.postbank.co.ug/ Official Website]\n\n{{Kampala District}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Postbank Uganda}}\n[[Category:Financial services companies of Uganda]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1926]]\n[[Category:Banks established in 1926]]\n[[Category:Kampala District]]\n[[Category:1926 establishments in Uganda]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company |\n  name   = PostBank Uganda|\n  logo   = |\n  type   = Private|\n  slogan = |\n  foundation     = 1926|\n  location       =  4 - 6 Nkrumah Road<br/>[[Kampala]], [[Uganda]] |\n  key_people     =  '''Obella Oode'''<br/>[[Chairman]] <br/> '''[[Julius Kakeeto]]'''<br/>[[Managing Director]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pmldaily.com/business/2019/11/postbank-uganda-announces-new-managing-director.html |date=11 November 2019 | publisher=PML Daily |author=Javia Ssebwami |access-date=3 April 2020 |last=Mugalu|date=3 June 2014|access-date=3 April 2020 |\ntitle=Post Bank Uganda announces new managing director |place=Kampala}}</ref>|\n  num_employees  = |\n  assets         = US$54 million<br/>(UGX:135.7 billion) (2012)|\n  revenue        ={{profit}} US$1.7 million<br/>(UGX:4.28 billion) (2012)|\n  industry       = [[Financial Services]]|\n  products       = [[Loans]], [[cheque|Checking]], [[Savings]], [[Investments]]|\n  homepage       = [http://www.postbank.co.ug/ Homepage]\n}}\n\n'''PostBank Uganda''' is a non-bank credit institution in [[Uganda]]. Its activities are supervised by the [[Bank of Uganda]], the country's [[central bank]] and national banking regulator.<ref name=\"Regulator\">{{cite web|first=.|last=BOU|accessdate=21 June 2015\n|url=https://www.bou.or.ug/opencms/bou/bou-downloads/financial_institutions/2013/CREDIT-INSTITUTIONS-CIs-AS-AT-MARCH-31-2013.pdf|tit